public class java_52424_CredentialValidator_A01 {
    private final String EXPECTED_PASSWORD; // Set it in your build configuration e.g., "secretPassword" via maven or gradle script, which can't do here because this is a standalone Java program without any external setup/dependencies:  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40528917/how-to-set-property-in-gradle
    
    public java_52424_CredentialValidator_A01() { // Default constructor for Dependency Injection (DI) in case your code is being used as a library by someone else or you just want to use this validator without any dependencies.  https://www.oracle.com/webfolder/technetwork/tutorials/obe/java/J2EE_InheritanceAndInterfacesPart1457063899-Summary.htm
        // By default, the password should be set in a build configuration and not hardcoded into this program:  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38205498/how-to-use-a-configurable-property-in-javafx-application#comment1761526
        // This is just a mock, the password should be stored in your own secure storage: https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration   For real world example and better practices you might want to use Spring security or Java's builtin Authentication API instead of this minimalist approach for learning purpose only
        // ExpectedPassword is set at compile time, we can not run the program without setting it. This should be done in a build configuration/environment variable (like Maven’s pom and gradle scripts).  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40528917/how-to-set-property-in-gradle
        // Also, the below line is not used here as it'll lead to a compile error because we don't have any external dependencies or setup for environment variables:  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36024197/how-to-set-properties-using-maven
        this.EXPECTED_PASSWORD = "secretPassword"; // This should be set at compile time via Maven's pom or gradle script, not hardcoded here in Java code e.g., https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38205498/how-to-use-a-configurable-property-in-javafx-application#comment1761526
    }  // End of Constructor Dependency Injection (DI) for the purpose mentioned in above comment. This can be used when someone else uses this code as a library and not directly run it on their own machine, or we want to use an instance that requires no environment setup/dependencies at compile time
    
    // Method responsible of checking if provided password is equal our expected value:  https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration   For real world example and better practices you might want to utilize Spring security or Java's Authentication API instead for this purpose only, but the concept would be similar
    public boolean validateCredentials(String providedPassword) {  // This method should not throw an exception if password is wrong otherwise it will lead into infinite loop. We can make our code more robust and secure by using exceptions or return a specific error message here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16059248/java-exception
        boolean validated = providedPassword != null && providedPassword.equals(EXPECTED_PASSWORD); // Check if the password is equal to our expected one, and return true or false accordingly  e.g., https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration
        System.out.println("Validation result: " + validated );// Print out a message with validation's results (true = password is correct; false=wrong) for debugging purposes only e.g., https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29817304/java-printing-out
        return validated; // Return true if the providedPassword matches our expected one, otherwise it will lead into an infinite loop (unless we have handled this case properly) here:  https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration   For real world example and better practices you might want to use Spring security or Java's Authentication API instead of the following logic
    } // End method validateCredentials(String providedPassword), which validates user password  https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration   For real world example and better practices you might want to use Spring security or Java's Authentication API instead for this purpose only
}//End of class CredentialsValidator e.g., http://tutorials.javacodegeeks.org/core-java/java-io-file-inputoutput-example/ https://www.baeldung.com/spring-boot-security # SecurityConfiguration   For real world example and better practices you might want to use Spring security or Java's Authentication API instead for this purpose only